<body>
<sec id="summary">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p><monospace>STON</monospace> (SofTware for petrOgraphic
  visualisatioN) is a tool designed to simplify the inspection of
  microscope images. Originally developed for petrography, specifically
  for analyzing mineral images, it can be used with any type of image.
  STON allows users to closely examine images, adjust parameters
  (contrast, brightness, sharpness), compare images side by side,
  combine multiple images and analyse features. Built with
  user-friendliness in mind, STON is fully customizable. It is developed
  in Python using the
  <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://wiki.qt.io/Qt_for_Python">PySide6</ext-link>
  library for the GUI, Pillow
  (<xref alt="Murray et al., 2025" rid="ref-MurrayU003A2025" ref-type="bibr">Murray
  et al., 2025</xref>) and matplotlib
  (<xref alt="Hunter, 2007" rid="ref-HunterU003A2007" ref-type="bibr">Hunter,
  2007</xref>) for image display and operation, and scikit-image
  (<xref alt="Walt et al., 2014" rid="ref-vanderwaltU003A2014" ref-type="bibr">Walt
  et al., 2014</xref>) for deeper image processing.</p>
</sec>
<sec id="statement-of-need">
  <title>Statement of need</title>
  <p>Thin-section petrography is a widely used technique in archaeology
  for analyzing the composition of ceramic and stone objects, as well as
  investigating their production technology and provenance
  (<xref alt="Peterson &amp; Betancourt, 2009" rid="ref-PetersonU003A2009" ref-type="bibr">Peterson
  &amp; Betancourt, 2009</xref>;
  <xref alt="Quinn, 2022" rid="ref-QuinnU003A2022" ref-type="bibr">Quinn,
  2022</xref>;
  <xref alt="Reedy, 2008" rid="ref-ReedyU003A2008" ref-type="bibr">Reedy,
  2008</xref>). This method involves studying these materials in thin
  sections mounted on glass slides under a polarizing microscope to
  examine their microscopic features. A critical aspect of
  archaeological study is the comparison and identification of patterns
  within these features across multiple samples. However, it is
  typically only possible to view one sample at a time under the
  microscope. As a result, this method relies heavily on visual memory
  and repeated observations, making the process inefficient and
  time-consuming, particularly when dealing with hundreds of
  samples.</p>
  <p>STON is designed to address these challenges by enabling users to
  observe multiple photomicrographs simultaneously within a single,
  convenient interface. It facilitates detailed comparisons, clustering,
  and data recording, which is especially important in ceramic paste
  analysis. By allowing users to view multiple samples side by side, the
  software supports efficient sample grouping and evaluation of
  compositional characteristics.</p>
  <p>Many existing image analysis tools used in microscopy (e. g.
  JMicrovision, ImageJ) provide basic functions such as image
  acquisition, single-image measurement, and annotation. However, these
  tools often focus on individual images rather than supporting the
  systematic comparison of large image sets, which is crucial for
  comprehensive petrographic and archaeometric research. They typically
  require manual handling of each image and often lack features for
  integrating multiple images into cohesive overviews, which are
  essential for detecting patterns and making reliable comparisons
  across samples, thereby supporting the archaeological interpretation
  process. Additionally, many of these tools include numerous plugins
  and complex functions that are not always straightforward or
  user-friendly for petrographic analysis, making the workflow more
  cumbersome for researchers. Commercial imaging software
  (e.g. JENOPTIK, PETROG), frequently tied to subscription models or
  bundled with hardware, is often limited by licensing costs and
  restricted flexibility, impeding open collaboration and
  reproducibility.</p>
  <p>STON addresses these limitations by providing an open-source,
  user-friendly platform specifically designed for petrographic image
  comparison. It offers tools for efficient image sorting, automated
  measurements, and the creation of composite overviews, enabling
  streamlined analysis of large datasets without requiring advanced
  technical skills or costly licenses. While tailored for the specific
  requirements of petrographic analysis in archaeology, the software has
  broader applications in other research fields that rely on visual
  image analysis. By providing an efficient and scalable tool for
  comparative analysis, it enhances research processes across various
  disciplines.</p>
</sec>
<sec id="the-graphical-user-interface">
  <title>The graphical user interface</title>
  <p>STON is a graphical user interface consisting of a main window (see
  <xref alt="[fig:GUI]" rid="figU003AGUI">[fig:GUI]</xref>) and multiple
  sub-windows for performing specific tasks. The main window serves as a
  central platform where images are loaded from disk and displayed as
  thumbnails.</p>
  <fig>
    <caption><p>Main window of
    STON.<styled-content id="figU003AGUI"></styled-content></p></caption>
    <graphic mimetype="image" mime-subtype="png" xlink:href="all_GUI_corrected.png" />
  </fig>
  <p>Designed to streamline researchers’ work, STON provides a
  comprehensive suite of tools for image analysis and visual inspection.
  It offers a user-friendly interface and visualization features, STON
  simplifies the process of inspecting, comparing, and manipulating
  images. All these tools are accessible from the main window, enabling
  users to explore images in greater detail, extract meaningful
  insights, and conduct in-depth analyses with ease.</p>
  <list list-type="bullet">
    <list-item>
      <p>Image detail and note-taking window: This window allows the
      user to inspect an image in greater detail. It also displays image
      metadata (currently supported for .tif files only) and provides
      options to adjust color, sharpness, brightness, and contrast.
      Additionally, it includes access to the analysis tool (see next
      section), enabling users to identify and study specific regions of
      interest.</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Side-by-Side Comparison Tool: Allows users to directly compare
      two images, making it easier to identify differences or
      similarities between samples. This feature is particularly useful
      in petrography and other disciplines where visual distinctions
      play a crucial role during the analysis.</p>
    </list-item>
    <list-item>
      <p>Image Cluster Tool (see
      <xref alt="[fig:cluster]" rid="figU003Acluster">[fig:cluster]</xref>):
      Facilitates the creation of image mashups by combining multiple
      images into a single composite. This is especially useful for
      merging images of the same material sample to create a unified
      visualization. Additionally, it supports the generation of
      meta-images, where all selected images are compiled into one
      comprehensive view, helping researchers analyze patterns and
      relationships across multiple images.</p>
    </list-item>
  </list>
  <fig>
    <caption><p>Image grouping. Mashup image (left): reconstruction of a
    complete sample; Meta-image (right): Cluster of images.
    <styled-content id="figU003Acluster"></styled-content></p></caption>
    <graphic mimetype="image" mime-subtype="png" xlink:href="cluster.png" />
  </fig>
  <sec id="feature-identification">
    <title>Feature identification</title>
    <p>STON offers a fast and easy-to-use analysis tool for identifying
    regions of interest within an image. The underlying algorithm is
    based on the
    <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://scikit-image.org/docs/stable/api/skimage.measure.html">measure
    module</ext-link> from the scikit-image library. It defines a region
    as a group of connected pixels sharing the same value. To account
    for pixel-to-pixel variations in the image, STON generates a binary
    image using a threshold set at the image’s average.</p>
    <fig>
      <caption><p>Regions identification in STON’s image analysis
      window.
      <styled-content id="figU003Aregions"></styled-content></p></caption>
      <graphic mimetype="image" mime-subtype="png" xlink:href="allregions.png" />
    </fig>
    <p>Users can then inspect all detected regions simultaneously (see
    <xref alt="[fig:regions]" rid="figU003Aregions">[fig:regions]</xref>)
    or examine them individually. Additionally, a catalog of region
    properties can be downloaded for further analysis.</p>
  </sec>
</sec>
